## 12. What Makes This Novel

> Most CI tools ask: "Does this code have tests?"
> Most code review asks: "Is this code readable?"
> SpecSync Agent asks: **"Does this code do what was specified?"**

| Differentiator | Why It Matters |
|---------------|---------------|
| **Spec-first validation** | Tests are generated from requirements, not from whatever the developer happened to build |
| **Vibe coding guardrail** | AI-generated code gets validated against human-authored architectural intent before it touches a PR |
| **Architect-owned KB** | The Wiki is the architect's domain. Developers cannot alter the spec — only the architect can change what counts as correct |
| **Bidirectional feedback** | When requirements genuinely change, the wiki gets updated through a structured PR process — not silently |
| **Wiki trigger** | The system is alive — a spec update automatically re-evaluates every blocked PR without developer action |
| **Branch hygiene** | Analysis files live only on feature branches. Main branch is never polluted with misalignment noise |
| **Zero new tools** | Everything lives in GitHub — wiki, actions, PR comments, check statuses. No external platforms required |
| **Distributed QA** | QA writes acceptance criteria in the wiki once. Every commit against that feature auto-generates tests from those criteria forever |

