## 13. Open Questions & Risks

| Risk | Mitigation |
|------|-----------|
| **Wiki cold start** — Spec pages need to exist before SpecSync adds value | Phase 4 onboarding wizard generates initial specs from existing code and README. Minimum viable wiki can be set up in under an hour. |
| **AI hallucination** — Claude may misread a diff or generate incorrect tests | Tests committed to feature branch only — developer reviews before PR merges. Low-confidence flags added to analysis output. |
| **Wiki webhook latency** — Relay adds a hop between wiki update and re-evaluation | Cloudflare Worker cold start is <50ms. Dispatch to Action start is typically <30 seconds. Architect-to-re-evaluation cycle is under 2 minutes. |
| **Relay is a single point of failure** — If the Worker is down, wiki trigger breaks | Code commit trigger still works independently. Wiki trigger failure is non-blocking — worst case, developer re-pushes to re-trigger. |
| **Spec page not found** — Developer builds a feature with no corresponding wiki page | SpecSync posts a warning: "No spec page found for this change area. Architect should create one before this PR is merged." PR is not blocked, but architect is notified. |
| **Integration test flakiness** — Auto-generated integration tests may need real fixtures | Phase 3 generates scaffolding with placeholder fixtures. Developers fill in realistic data. Full fixture generation in Phase 4. |
| **API costs at scale** — High-frequency commit repos generate significant Claude API costs | Per-branch rate limiting. Diff deduplication for near-identical commits. Cost dashboard in Phase 4. |
| **Multi-language scope** — Test generation quality varies by language | MVP: TypeScript/JavaScript + Python only. Java, Go added in Phase 4 based on demand. |
| **False positive misalignments** — Spec is ambiguous, Claude interprets differently each run | Confidence score on every verdict. Developer feedback loop (confirmed alignments) improves calibration over time. |

